Prologue
"Please!", the queen Eirwen pleaded. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The king of Ice looked at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor next to him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at this thought.
The little girl looked a lot like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair with blue streaks. The king of Ice thought that a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into nature. That's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat her name as if it were poison. He did that all the time.
Frostwell had not always been one kingdom. It had been split in two, the North and the South. To the north, the non-magical kingdom. To the south, a kingdom full of fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms tore each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodbath. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would ally itself with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I implore you, my lord, in exchange for the life of my child, do whatever you want to me, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding tightly to her child in her arms.
The King of Ice looked down at his wife with disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one he had lived with for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Alright, the child will be allowed to live in the palace," he began, extracting a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified look. She lowered her gaze slowly. "Yes, my lord," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered his royal advisor to take the child to one of the vacant apartments of Eirwen. Once this was done, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the inhabitants of the village could attend the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the inhabitants cried out in indignation at seeing their only queen, the kindest, on the verge of being killed. Some people were crying, others were screaming and trying to attack the guards, while others still wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the person most feared in the kingdom made her entrance. The fire user. Ex-Queen Eirwen was going to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the most cruel punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the fire user set the gallows on fire, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the ex-queen.
"Survive, Kari". This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room to the left of the south wing of the always frozen palace. The assistants who passed in front of it always wondered what was inside, frightened by what could be found within. The rumors of the maids danced in the corridors. It was thought that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in this room, awaiting her liberation.
"They could not be further in error," thought Ivory as she walked towards the south wing, while the assistants went back and forth murmuring among themselves. They have no idea what's inside.
Bien sûr, these rumors also applied to her, as she was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Tap, tap. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; whispered Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
She wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when she had asked her to.  I still have bruises from the last time.  Ivory chuckled at the memory.  Kari had thrown a book on her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
Only one knock came from inside, suggesting that she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I enter?", asked Ivory, remembering the time when she had done so without asking permission.
A sound hit from inside. It seemed to mean yes. Ivory shivered, from cold, but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room that was supposed to be empty, even if she had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door gently. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to the norms of normal people, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder in the room than in the rest of the palace (and that was not little to say). A snowstorm seemed to have hit inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her quilt, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit the space.
"Which notebook is this?", asked Ivory in sitting down next to Kari on her bed.
